03762nmm a2200541Ia 9781501726583DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20182009nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017265837 a10.7591/97815017265832doi  a(DE-B1597)515621  a(OCoLC)1100462960  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHQ766.5.C6bW485 2006eb04a363.9/609512231 aWhite, Tyrene, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChina's Longest Campaign :bBirth Planning in the People's Republic, 1949–2005 /cTyrene White. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b10 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the late 1970s, just as China was embarking on a sweeping program of post-Mao reforms, it also launched a one-child campaign. This campaign, which cut against the grain of rural reforms and childbearing preferences, was the culmination of a decade-long effort to subject reproduction to state planning. Tyrene White here analyzes this great social engineering experiment, drawing on more than twenty years of research, including fieldwork and interviews with a wide range of family-planning officials and rural cadres.White explores the origins of China's "birth-planning" approach to population control, the implementation of the campaign in rural China, strategies of resistance employed by villagers, and policy consequences (among them infanticide, infant abandonment, and sex-ratio imbalances). She also provides the first extensive political analysis of China's massive 1983 sterilization drive. The birth-planning project was the last and longest of the great mobilization campaigns, surviving long after the Deng regime had officially abandoned mass campaigns as instruments of political control.Arguing that the campaign had become an indispensable institution of rural governance, White shows how the one-child campaign mimicked the organizational style and rhythms both of political campaigns and economic production campaigns. Against the backdrop of unfolding rural reforms, only the campaign method could override obstacles to rural enforcement. As reform gradually eroded and transformed patterns of power and authority, however, even campaigns grew increasingly ineffective, paving the way for long-overdue reform of the birth-planning program.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aBirth controlxGovernment policyzChinaxHistoryy20th century. 4aAsian Studies. 4aHistory.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172658340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501726583423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501726583/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles